qx|B2|ht|e|cp|4|cs|1|at|^-{    General Consideration    }
^-|CS||CP|1|at|^b@2^Z@3Movie Maker(MM): |CP||AT|Thank you Kiamemnon for taking time and coming down from Mount Olympus to our land and answering my questions on Weak Two Bids. I will start with the first soon. Earlier you mentioned that the Weak Two Bids are not new.|PG||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^Z@3^*BKiamemnon: ^*N|cp||at|The Weak Two Bid, as you might imagine, is an opening bid at the two level that shows a weak hand, rather than a strong hand. The concept of using opening two-level bids for weak hands has been around since the days of auction bridge—the forerunner of the game of contract bridge that we play today.|PG||AT| 

Harold Vanderbilt, often credited with the invention of contract bridge while cruising aboard a ship in 1925, included Weak Two Bids as part of his Vanderbilt Club System, one of the first complete bidding systems. The modern version of this convention was popularized by Howard Schenken, considered by many people to be the best bridge player of all time.|PG||CP|1|at|
^b@2^Z@3MM: |CP||AT|Very interesting. I am a bit partial to Louis Watson but you know best.|PG||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^Z@3^*BKiamemnon: ^*N|cp||at|Let me add. Most hands are opened at the one level, so that the partnership has as much room as possible to search for the best contract. Opening bids at the two level have traditionally been used as strong Two Bids, showing a hand too strong to open at the one level—no longer true. |PG||AT|

However, now opening bids in a suit at the two level (2@D, 2@h, and 2@S) or higher are commonly used to show hands with a long suit, too weak to open at the one level. These are ^*Ipreemptive opening bids^*N and, as you may know, they can make life difficult for the opponents. This tactic has proven so successful that many players today prefer to use methods that allow them to preempt more frequently. I'll show you a few examples. |PG||nt||
%%%page 2
ht|d|CP|1|at|^b@2^Z@3MM: |CP||AT|What do you mean by ^*Ipreemptive opening bids can make life difficult for the opponents.^*N?|PG||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^Z@3^*BKiamemnon: ^*N|cp||at|Simple. You crowd out their bidding space and they cannot properly exchange information and arrive at an optimal contract. Better yet, they may over-react and over bid their hand which gives the other side good boards. As an added important benefit it gives good opening lead information to the pre-emptor's partner. The best is giving adequate information to the partner. Armed with good information partner can set the appropriate course and arrive at another and possibly better auction. A Weak Two Bid at first and third seat usually is more powerful. BTW, have you read the good article on Weak Two Bids by Eddie Kantar at|CP|1|AT| ^*Hwww.kantarbridge.com/weak_2s.htm^*N?|PG||CP|1|at|
^b@2^Z@3MM: |CP||AT|Of course I have read it. Let me even quote the part about the The Advantages of Weak Two Bids from that article:|PG||
