^-|ht|c|cp|8|AT|^B@2^Z@3^*BKiamemnon: ^*N|cp||at|Now I will get into the difficult part of Weak Two Bids—HCPs, shape, vulnerability, and position. We cannot set meaningful standards for each without considering all four.|PG||CP|1|at|
^b@2^Z@3MM: |CP||AT|That is the reason why experts vary so much when bidding Weak Two.|PG||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^Z@3^*BKiamemnon: ^*N|cp||at|That is correct. Let me address the scoring for penalties and how it is affected by both doubles and vulnerability—assuming you are doubled after a Weak Two Bid and the opponents set you. When non-vulnerable, the penalty scale for doubled undertricks goes 100, 300, 500, 800, 1100, etc. When vulnerable, the scale goes 200, 500, 800, 1100, etc. The value of game for the opponents is approximately 500 points. As a result, you can rarely afford to go down more than three tricks when non-vulnerable or two tricks when vulnerable. When the opponents are non-vulnerable and your side is vulnerable, you want to be especially careful. That means your HCP and suit quality should be at the top of the scale. |PG||CP|1|at|
^b@2^Z@3MM: |CP||AT|That is great information. Before you go further please address the six-card requirement.|PG||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^Z@3^*BKiamemnon: ^*N|cp||at|You ask, “Why a six-card suit and not a seven-card suit?" (A seven-card suit is opened 3 level.) With a good seven-card suit and a hand too weak to open at the one level, you usually open a preemptive bid at the three level, rather than the two level. If you have a five-card suit, it's a little dangerous to be opening at the two level—although as you'll see later there are exceptions.|PG||ht|s|AT|^b@2^r@3The other feature of the hand on the right (from the first example) is that it contains too few points to open the bidding 1@S. The point requirement for opening Weak Two varies among the experts. You'll see ranges such as 6 to 10, 5 to 10 or 5 to 11 for a Weak Two Bid. The guideline by Eddie Kantar is 7-9 HCP. Of course ACBL SAYC System Booklet says 5-11 points.|ht|s|va|6|at|^s|ih|SAQJT87H87DJT8C87|PG||ht|v|va|6|cp|8|AT|
^B@2^Z@3^*BKiamemnon: ^*N|cp||at|One more point. To use Weak Two Bid, there has to be some way to handle hands which would have been opened with a strong Two Bid. When playing Weak Two Bids, one bid is reserved for all strong hands. The 2@C opening bid is used to handle all strong hands of about 22 or more points.|PG||NT||bt||
