^-|ht|c|cp|1|AT|^B@2^Z@3^*BMM: ^*N|cp||at|In a nutshell tell me what might influence your decision in opening Weak Two.|PG||cp|8|AT|^B@2^Z@3^*BKiamemnon: ^*N|cp||at|There are two—^*BVulnerability^*N and ^*Bposition at the table^*N. Let me give you some of my thoughts.|PG||AT|
^C@2^Z@3^*BVulnerability^*N. If you are vulnerable, you want to be more cautious. If you were doubled for penalties in a Weak Two auction, you might take only three or four tricks if partner has no help. That could be a penalty of 1100 to 1400 points. Even if the opponents can make a slam, they have more to gain by doubling you if they are not vulnerable.|PG||AT| 
^C@2^Z@3^*BPosition at the table^*N. Suppose you are in third position holding the hand we looked at before (shown again below), and you are not vulnerable and the opponents are vulnerable.| 
HT|l|at|^C|ih|1ST8H87DQJT876CK87|pg||ht|l|at|^g@2^Z@3The hand on the left isn't a bad hand to take a chance on opening 2@D. Since partner passed originally, it's very likely that your opponents can make at least a game, perhaps a slam.|pg|| 
ht|p|at|^B@2^Z@3Anything you can do to disrupt their auction may get you a good result. When they are vulnerable and you are not, the opponents will be reluctant to double you. They would have to defeat you four tricks—for a penalty of 800 points—to compensate for the value of their game.|PG||at| 

So, the Weak Two Bid is another tool in your tool kit. You choose the appropriate moment to bring it out and use it. Let us move on. I have to cover more fine points.|PG||NT||
