ST||MD|1ST2 HJ87632dJ56 CAK,,,|sv|o|rh||AH|Hand 11|mb|?|lb|*bWhat would you do as dealer?^^P|cp|8|AT|^B@2^Z@3^*BKiamemnon: ^*N|cp||at|Pass is the correct bid. You have a six-card suit and 9 high-card points, but your suit isn't very good. Avoid opening a Weak Two Bid with a poor suit and most of your strength outside of the suit. When you have a poor suit, there's too much risk that the opponents will be willing to defend for penalties. Also, the more strength you have outside your suit, the less likely that the opponents can make a game. Even a small penalty might be too much.|mb|p|PG||NT|| 
%%hand 12
ST||MD|1ST7 HKJT876 DJ76 CAK,,,|sv|o|rh||AH|Hand 12|mb|?|lb|*bWhat would you do as dealer?^^1h|cp|8|AT|^B@2^Z@3^*BKiamemnon: ^*N|cp||at|Bid 1@H. You have a good six-card suit, but the hand is too strong for a Weak Two Bid.|MB|1h|PG||NT||
%%hand 13
ST||MD|1SKT87HKJT876DJT8C—,,,|sv|o|rh||AH|Hand 13|mb|?|lb|*bWhat would you do as dealer?^^p|cp|8|AT|^B@2^Z@3^*BKiamemnon: ^*N|cp||at|Hold on to your hat old man. This is where you can get into trouble. First let us see what the so called main stream recommends. With six-card good quality suit and 8 high-card points a Weak Two has merit—bid 2@H. However, the conventional wisdom and probably ACBL have it that South should not bid 2@H because the hand has 4-card major and a void. Let us listen to the reasoning.|PG||NT||cp|8|AT|^B@2^Z@3^*BKiamemnon: ^*N|cp||at|As a general guideline, you should not open a hand Weak Two when you have a side four-card major suit ( a weak four-card major is okay) or a void. Your Weak Two Bid may make the auction more difficult for the opponents, but it can also make the auction more difficult for your partner.|PG||NT||cp|8|AT|^B@2^Z@3^*BKiamemnon: ^*N|cp||at|It is maintained that when you have a side four-card major suit, there are other possibilities. Partner might have a singleton heart and four or five spades—in this case. Partner won't want to bid spades because that might get the partnership into more trouble. You could go down in a part score in hearts when you could make something—perhaps a game—with spades as trumps.|PG||NT||cp|8|AT|^B@2^Z@3^*BKiamemnon: ^*N|cp||at|Also, a void is very powerful and makes it difficult for partner to estimate the playing strength of the combined hands. If partner has something like the Club Queen and two low clubs, partner will be expecting to lose two or three tricks in that suit opposite a normal Weak Two Bid. Partner won't expect that there are no club losers on this hand. |PG||NT||cp|8|AT|^B@2^Z@3^*BKiamemnon: ^*N|cp||at|So, the general guideline is to avoid opening a Weak Two Bid when you have a side four-card major suit or a void. It's only a guideline—you're free to exercise your judgment on any hand. As you mentioned, to me, your mentor has rather strong feelings on this topic. Let us look at what he has to say.|PG||cp|1|AT|

