^B@2^*BSchutzmenelaus: ^*N|cp||at| I would open West hand 2@S. It is much more effective to preempt early than to come in later. Further, I disagree with those who say you cannot bid a weak 2 with an outside 4 card major. A preempt is most effective the earlier you bid it.|PG||NT|^B@2
hope: I did not have a good preempt and do not preempt partner in first seat :(.|PG||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*BSchutzmenelaus: ^*N|cp||at|I still do, but I would understand if you chose not to bid it at unfavorable vulnerability. Here, let me discuss preempting theory.|PG||NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*BSchutzmenelaus: ^*N|cp||at|In first seat, a preempt is odds on to work because if you have a weak hand, that leaves more points for the opponents. A preempt is even more appropriate in third seat since there are 2 passes, and you have a weak hand, it is almost certain that fourth seat has a good hand.|PG||NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*BSchutzmenelaus: ^*N|cp||at|The only time you should be a little more cautious with a preempt is second seat because then it is more likely that partner has a good hand and you will be preempting partner. If first seat passes, and you have a weak hand, that leaves more points for partner to have. So, if you are worried about preempting partner, only worry about it in second seat.|PG||NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*BSchutzmenelaus: ^*N|cp||at|Personally, I never worry about it, lol. Remember, the earlier you preempt the more effective it is. The more chance you give the opponents to exchange information, the less effective a preempt is. ^*uOn the other hand, to be ACBL main stream you should follow the rule of two out of three or three out five honors.^*n|PG||at| But my guess would be something like "1 of top 3 and 2 of top 5" is more main stream these days. |PG||NT||cp|1|AT|
