^B@2^*BSchutzmenelaus: ^*N|cp||at|I believe that you can and should open a weak 2 with an outside 4-card major. The argument for not opening is that you might miss a 4-4 major suit game, but there are very few deals where opening a weak 2 with a 4-card major will cause your side to miss game. Even with a 4-4 fit, on most hands, you will be better off playing in your 6-card suit -- extra trump length is a big asset when playing in a suit contract. Weak 2@S are very good bidding weapons, and should be employed whenever possible. |PG||NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*BSchutzmenelaus: ^*N|cp||at|They are much less effective if you pass originally and perhaps come in later, because then you have given the opponents a chance to exchange information at a low level. For the few hands where you might  miss a 4-4 major suit game by opening a weak 2, there are many more hands where you would have gained had you opened a weak 2 and failed to do so because of your 4-card major. Marty Bergen also believes there is nothing wrong with opening a weak 2 with an outside 4-card major.|PG||cp|1|AT|

