%%%% Section B5 Weak Two Bids makes life difficult for the Opponents 
QX|b5,Weak Two Bids makes life difficult for the Opponents|CS|6|AT|^-
{      Weak Two Bids make life difficult for the Opponents     }
^-|ht|c|cp|8|AT|^B@2^Z@3Kiamemnon: ^*N|cp||at|I think by now you have a good grasp of Weak Two Bids as to point range, quality of the suit and how to effectively use them.  Next, let us look at why a so-called pesky Weak Two preempt can make life difficult for the opponents.  I would like to remind you, however, that such an outcome is not always true.  Occasionally it works as a boomerang.  Please see the following board.|PG||nt||
%%%%% Board
ST||MD|1,SJ87 HQ J876DK8CA J8,,|sv|o|rh||AH|Hand E1|mb|p?|cp|8|AT|^B@2^Z@3Kiamemnon: ^*N|cp||at|You are West and South (the Dealer) passes.|pg||lb|*bPlease make your bid.^^1h|mb|1h|at| That is easy. You have 12 high-card points plus 1 for the five-card suit, enough to open the bidding 1@H. You've started to describe your hand to partner, and you'll see where the bidding takes you from there.|PG||NT|^B@2
Now, to prove a point let us suppose South opens 2@S instead of passing.|pg||UB|2|mb|2s|at| What would you bid now?|PG||at| Does South's bid affect your bidding?|PG||AT| Absolutely.|PG||AT| You do not see his hand but everyone at the table has a fairly good idea what he has--a weak hand with six-card spades as is shown next.|pg||md|0SAKT532H4DJT65C56,0,0,0|PG||NT|^B@2
When South opens the bidding with a Weak Two, you have three choices. If you want to come into the bidding, you can overcall at three level or you can make a takeout double. You also can pass.|PG||NT|^B@2
A three-level overcall should be based on a good six-card or longer suit and better than your minimum hand. Further, you are poorly placed to step into the middle of the auction. You know nothing about your partner's hand. North, on the other hand, has a good description of South's hand. North also is in a good position to double you for penalties if you step out of line.|PG||NT|^B@2
Say you make a takeout double. Fair enough. However, a takeout double generally shows support for the other three unbid suits. You have good support for hearts and some support for clubs, but what if partner chooses 3@D after your takeout double?|PG||NT|^B@2
You probably say you could correct the 3@D to 3@H. But that is compounding your error as double and correct promises a much stronger hand than you have.|PG||NT|^B@2
You have to admit that the 2@S bid by South has given you no alternative except making a Pass as anything else is very risky.|PG||AT| Nevertheless, let us look at what could happen if you bid 3@H.|MB|3h|PG||AT| North doubles with the hand shown above, along with East's hand.|mb|dppp|md|0,0,S6HA KTH3 DAQ74 CK Q79,0|PG||AT| The double should not be a surprise, however.|PG||md|0,0,0,SQ94H952D932CT234|at| If this is the full hand, the defenders will defeat the contract at least four tricks. The penalty would be greater than any score North/South would get if West stays put after the Weak Two bid by South.|PG||NT|^B@2
The result would not be any better if West makes a takeout double.|Ub|5|pg||MB|dp|PG||AT| East would probably bid 3@C,|MB|3c|PG||AT| and that is even worse than 3@H.|MB|ppdppp|PG||AT| Whatever East–West do after the Weak Two bid by South, North is likely to double and extract a sizeable penalty.|PG||NT|^B@2
West's safest option is to pass. The auction isn't over yet, and East might hold a better hand and come into the auction.|PG||NT|| 

st||sk|e|md|1SAKT532H4DJT65C56,SJ87HQJ876DK8CA J8,s96ha532dq742cq97,SQ4Hkt9Da93CTk234|sv|o|rh||AH|Hand E1a|NT|^B@2
Let us keep the hands for South and West the same and tweak the hand for East as shown above. Also assume, for the purpose of making a point, that East is the dealer.|pg||lb|*bWhat would East bid?^^1c|at| East most likely would open this hand 1@C.|PG||AT| However, in this auction South is the dealer and bids 2@S which both West and North pass.|pg||MB|2sPP?|nt||lb|*bWhat should East bid?^^p|NT|^B@2
East has the same dilemma West had. East can pass, make a takeout double or overcall 3@C. |PG||NT|^B@2
Takeout double is not advisable—three-card support for hearts and diamonds. East has only so-so support for both hearts and diamonds. If partner picks hearts, for example, East may be in a 4–3 fit at the three level—and after South's 2@S opening bid, it's more than likely that hearts are breaking badly.|PG||NT|^B@2
3@C overcall is dangerous. With only a five-card suit—and not a very good one at that. It would be very dangerous to introduce it at the three level. In addition, your spade Queen is of dubious value once South opens 2@S. As you've just seen, even though South has a weak hand, North could still have a strong hand. So, what is East likely to do with this hand?|PG||AT| Passing seems like the best option.|PG||AT| Let's see how this works out.|mb|ppp|SK||PG||NT|^B@2  
What's going to happen to South in the 2@S contract?|PG||AT| South will probably finish with eight tricks and make the contract. With spades breaking 3–2, South will probably lose one spade trick, two diamond tricks and two club tricks. South makes 2@S.|PG||NT|^B@2 
On the other hand, what would have happened if South had passed originally?|Ub|6|pg||MB|P|PG||AT| West would open the bidding 1@H,|MB|1hP|PG||AT| and East would respond 2@C.|MB|2cP3cp4hppp|PG||AT| East has enough strength to take the partnership to the game level in hearts, but an immediate raise would show four-card or longer support.|PG||NT|^B@2
Even if South now comes in with an overcall of 2@S, it's too late. East knows the partnership has an eight-card heart fit and enough combined strength for game. East will get the partnership to 4H.|PG||NT|^B@2
How would East–West fare in a contract of 4H? West might make that contract. West has three spade losers, but the third loser can be ruffed in dummy or eventually discarded on the club suit. If the defenders lead spades, the spade Jack will become a trick. There's a sure heart loser and there's a potential club loser. West will probably have to guess which defender holds the club Queen in order to make the contract. |PG||NT|^B@2
Not a bad 4@H contract. Without the 2@S opening bid, North might even lead a club on opening lead, taking away the guess. If South does overcall 2@S, declarer is most likely to play North for the club Queen—since South has long spades and didn't open the bidding.|PG||NT|^B@2
So, South's 2@S bid is a success. South will make 2@S when the opponents have a reasonable chance of making game in hearts. Even if East–West were to go down in 4@H, the penalty would be less than the score North–South receives for making 2@S.|PG||NT|^B@2
In conclusion you can see how the Weak Two Bid might be effective. It takes up just enough bidding room to make the auction difficult for the opponents. They have to start making decisions at the two or three level.|PG||NT|^B@2
Should you expect such a result all the time? Not really. But it happens more often than not.|PG||NT||bt||
