%%%%%% Responding to a Weak Two Bid
qx|B6,Responding to a Weak Two Bid|CS|6|AT|^-
{      Responding to a Weak Two Bid     }
^-|ht|b|va|3|cp|8|AT|^B@2^Z@3Kiamemnon: ^*N|cp||at|It has been a long session old man. Do you want to continue or shall I stop for a while. I understand that at your age you may be due for a nap. Of course you could have napped during most of my discussion!|PG||cp|1|AT|
^B@2^Z@3MM: ^*N|cp||at|Press on My King. I have been attentive all the time. I am particularly keen to listen to your discussion of how to respond to Weak Two Bids. I know of a few. Howard prefers Ogust. However, he recommends that we to fully discuss it with our partner whatever option we decide to play.|PG||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^Z@3Kiamemnon: ^*N|cp||at|Well he is a wise man and he is correct. I will explain those conventions later. However, let us deal with simple stuff first before getting into using gadgets.|PG||AT|

As you already learned, the Weak Two Bid is primarily a defensive type of opening bid. It's designed to make the bidding difficult for the opponents, but it also gives responder a good description of opener's hand. Let's see how responder should handle such a bid. Further, let us suppose that the opponents do not interfere with the bidding. I will address interference later.|PG||AT| When your partner opens a Weak Two and the next player passes, responder must consider his/her options: |PG||AT|^*Bpass, |PG||AT|raise to below game,|PG||AT| raise to game,|PG||AT| bid another suit,|PG||AT| or, possibly consider slam based on hand strength.^*N|PG||AT|

The first two options are what happens in the majority of auctions, and I deal with them first. Let us keep the North-South hands from the last example, which I will bring up next. |PG||cp|1|AT|

^B@2^*BMM: ^*N|cp||at|My wise King and favorite of Gods and Goddesses we have been learning that the Law of Total Tricks is the single most important guideline in the competitive bidding. In fact a simple version of it (the Bergen version) says:|PG||AT|
^-
{    IT IS SAFE  TO  COMPETE TO THE SAME  LEVEL AS THE ## OF TRUMPS YOUR SIDE HAS.    }
^-|PG||at|
So if we have an 8-card fit, we can raise to the 2-level (8 trick contract). With a 9-card  fit, we can raise to the 3-level. And with a 10-card fit, we can compete to the 4-level.|PG||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^Z@3Kiamemnon: ^*N|cp||at|I am delighted that you know about the Law. The LAW is a really good guideline. It is  much better even than most expert judgement. HCP are irrelevant on most hands. There are occasional hands where it is off by a trick but they are few and far between. Now stop interrupting and let me continue.|PG||nt||
