{      The 2NT Response to a Weak Two Bid    }

{    Introduction    }
^-|cp|8|AT|^B@2^Z@3^*BKiamemnon:  ^*N|cp||at|Although a Weak Two bid is very descriptive, beside being disruptive, there are times when responder needs more information to determine the best contract. Responder needs to know whether opener has a minimum or a maximum for the Weak Two Bid and whether there is a fit present. Let us look at two hands side by side:|PG||
ht|h|at|^b  |ih|s8 7 dK Q T 7 4 3 hJ 7 6 c5 3|ht|H|at|^v|ih|s8 7 dK Q T 7 4 3 ha J 6 c5 3|pg||
ht|h|at|^b  |ih|s8 7 dK Q T 7 4 3 hJ 7 6 c5 3|ht|h|at|^v|ih|s8 7 dK Q T 7 4 3 ha J 6 c5 3|HT|G|va|4|AT|^f@2^V@3Both are classic hands for opening Weak Two. However the hand on the left with 6 HCP is at the bottom and the hand on the right with 10 HCP is at the top of the 5-11 HCP range for Weak Two bids. Further, the hand on the right has a great side suit in hearts. This feature combined with 10 HCP could be a good fit for responder to be in a game—probably in 3N. But how can opener convey this information to the Responder ? |PG||
ht|n|AT|^B@2There are two popular treatments or conventions to solve this problem:|pg||
ht|n|AT|^B@2There are two popular treatments or conventions to solve this problem:|
HT|o|at|^C2NT-Show a Feature|pg||
ht|n|AT|^B@2There are two popular treatments or conventions to solve this problem:|
HT|o|at|^C2NT-Show a Feature|
ht|p|at|^C2NT-Ogust|PG||
ht|q|at|^B@2^Z@3In both Responder with a suitable hand, assuming there is no interference, bids 2NT. Some partnerships use 2NT-easy Ogust or other conventions for the same purpose. However, I believe your partnership would do fine by playing either 2NT-Show a Feature or 2NT-Ogust. Regardless, the 2NT bid is 100% forcing.|PG||cp|1|AT|
^B@2^Z@3^*BMM:  ^*N|cp||at|My bridge mentor, Howard Schutzman, plays 2NT-Ogust.|PG||cp|8|AT|^B@2^Z@3^*BKiamemnon:  ^*N|cp||at|Great. I will teach you the 2NT-Show a Feature and ask him to explain the 2NT-Ogust. |PG||NT||
