^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|If your partner opens a Weak Two, and you bid 2N, that is a conventional bid asking partner for a further description of their Weak Two bid. It asks both about suit quality and HCP. Let me define a few terms important to Ogust convention.|PG||
ht|h|AT|"Bad suit" is one lacking two of the top three honors. |PG||
ht|h|AT|"Bad suit" is one lacking two of the top three honors. 
"Good suit" is one with two of top three honors. A suit headed by AK AQ or KQ.|PG||
ht|h|AT|"Bad suit" is one lacking two of the top three honors. 
"Good suit" is one with two of top three honors. A suit headed by AK AQ or KQ.
"Bad  hand", has 5-7 HCP.|PG||
ht|h|AT|"Bad suit" is one lacking two of the top three honors. 
"Good suit" is one with two of top three honors. A suit headed by AK AQ or KQ.
"Bad  hand", has 5-7 HCP.
"Good hand", has 8-10 HCP.|PG||ht|l|AT|

So, your suit either is "Bad" or "Good" and you either have "Bad" or "Good" hand. Therefore, there are 4 combinations you can talk about "good/bad hand" and "good/bad suit." And, thus there are four responses.|PG||
ht|p|at|3@C bid promises a "Bad Hand" and a "Bad Suit" hand--Bad/Bad.|PG||
ht|p|at|3@C bid promises a "Bad Hand" and a "Bad Suit" hand--Bad/Bad.
3@D bid promises a "Bad Hand" and a "Good Suit" hand-- Bad/Good.|PG||
ht|p|at|3@C bid promises a "Bad Hand" and a "Bad Suit" hand--Bad/Bad.
3@D bid promises a "Bad Hand" and a "Good Suit" hand-- Bad/Good.
3@H bid promises a "Good Hand" and a "Bad Suit" hand--Good/Bad.|PG|| 
ht|p|at|3@C bid promises a "Bad Hand" and a "Bad Suit" hand--Bad/Bad.
3@D bid promises a "Bad Hand" and a "Good Suit" hand-- Bad/Good.
3@H bid promises a "Good Hand" and a "Bad Suit" hand--Good/Bad.
3@S bid promises a "Good Hand" and a "Good Suit" hand--Good/Good.|PG||
ht|t|at|So, a minor suit bid shows a bad hand, and a major suit bid shows a good hand point count wise. Therefore, in the hand we just played, I play  that 3@D shows a bad hand with a good suit, and 3@H shows a good hand and a bad suit. However, there is another variation that Leandro plays which simply reverses 3@D and 3@H. In his version 3@D (which is what he bid originally) shows a good hand and a bad suit  and 3@H shows a bad hand and a good suit. In this variation the minors show a bad suit, and the majors show a good suit in his version. I don't think it matters which you play, although I believe, at least in the US, the version I play is more popular. But obviously you need to check with your partner.|PG||cp|1|AT|

