^B@2^*BMovie Maker: ^*N|cp||at|Howard, that was great explanation. But let us assume my partner opens a Weak Two (2@D for example) and the next opponent passes. What type of hand do I need to bid conventional 2N?|PG||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Before I get into specific let me give you a key messages of using Ogust convention. You should not overuse Ogust. The law of total tricks and your dummy points often tell you what to do. Ogust only should be used for those in-between hands, which do not occur all that often.|PG||cp|1|AT|
^B@2^*BMovie Maker: ^*N|cp||at|Then, would you please give us your guideline.|PG||
cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Let me first discuss what to do when partner opens 2@H or 2@S. In that case, your first thought should be whether or not you want to play in game in opener's suit. It is almost always easier to play in a suit, particularly when one hand is weak, than it is to play in NT. And your primary guideline should be the Law of Total Tricks. So, let us say you are on the table and partner bids let us say 2@H and you have the following hands. First, you choose your bid then I will give you my critique and recommendations. I will be your partner. For clarity we are not going to show the entire hand.|PG||cp|1|AT|

^B@2^*BMovie Maker: ^*N|cp||at|Earlier in the presentation, Kiamemnon explained this section. However, it would not hurt to hear it from a mortal bridge expert too :).|PG||nt||
