ST||pn|Partner,,You,|sk|N|MD|1st9 hkqj432 dkt2 c23,,sj87 ha567 d3 ca4567,|sv|o|rh||ah|Handling Interference|AH|Quiz Ia|MB|2h2s?|lb|*bWhat do you bid now?^^4h|mb|4h|NT|^B@2  
4@H is the best response from the three options of Pass, or 3H, or 4@H. Partner has a good heart suit and not much strength outside of hearts. You probably can take six heart tricks and the @cA. If partner has some length in diamonds, partner can probably ruff one or two diamonds in dummy. Partner should be able to take eight or nine tricks in a heart contract.|PG||NT|^B@2
On the other hand it is quite likely the opponents can make game or more in spades. It's unlikely that partner has much in spades. Therefore, if you are defending 4@S, it's doubtful your side will get any tricks in that suit. If the opponents' hearts divide 2–1, you'll get a heart trick-your partnership has ten hearts. |PG||NT|^B@2
If they divide 3–0, you won't get any heart tricks. You should get a trick with the @cA, but you won't get any more tricks unless partner comes up with something.  |PG||NT|^B@2
You don't expect to go down too badly, even if the opponents double. If they do double, the penalty is likely to be less than the value of the game they can make. They may not even double the 4@H contract, being afraid that you have a stronger hand.|PG||NT|^B@2
If they bid, they may misjudge the situation and get too high. At worst, they'll reach their normal contract of 4@S, and you will have lost nothing.|PG||NT|^B@2 
A tactical underbid of 3@H, hoping the opponents will stop in 3@S, or an immediate jump to 5@H, hoping the opponents will misjudge what to do are worth your consideration.|PG||NT|^B@2
To prove a point, let's see how will partner fare in 4@H doubled if East doubles the 4@H contract, rather than bidding 4@S.|PG||MB|xppp|sk||PG||NT|^B@2
Most likely down one. Partner will lose two spades, one diamond and one club. Partner's other diamond losers can be ruffed in dummy if necessary. Down one doubled is not bad result because East/West have no difficulty making 4@S.|PG||NT|^B@2
You say you are not convinced. Fair enough. Let us randomly divide the remaining 26 cards between East/West and take a look.|PG||ub|4|pg||pf|y|mb|4sppp|PG||md|0,sa65432h9daj75cqj ,0,skqht8dq9864ckt98 |SB|EI have a random hand.|PG||SB|WThey gave me a random hand too. Not a bad hand since you pushed us to 4S :).|PG||NT|^B@2
You have at most one heart trick, a club trick for sure and maybe a trick with partner's @dK. Therefore East–West should make their 4@S contract with ease.|SB|E|SB|W|PG||NT|^B@2
The jump to 4@H makes the auction much more difficult for East–West to judge exactly what to do. If East bids 4S, rather than doubling, West might decide to bid more. If the opponents get to the five level, they could go down. Such is the nature of preemptive bids. It makes the game of bridge quite exciting, and the results can be unpredictable.|PG||NT|^B@2
Would it make any difference if West had doubled 2@H, with a different hand than the random we just gave him, instead of over­calling 2@S?|PG||AT| No. North should jump to 4@H, hoping the opponents will guess incorrectly about what to do.|PG||NT|^B@2
